OL,6,FExactly a century ago, in 1923, the
OL,7,Feminent biologist J.B.S. Haldane wrote
OL,8,Fan essay called "Science and the
OL,9,FFuture".
OL,11,FFour hundred years in the future, he
OL,12,Fpredicted, England would run on
OL,13,Fhydrogen. A network of windmills would
OL,14,Fproduce energy that would split the
OL,15,Foxygen from the hydrogen in water; the
OL,16,Fhydrogen would be liquified and kept as
OL,17,Ffuel. That fuel could be used for
OL,18,Findustry, heating, lighting, and
OL,19,Ftransportation. In particular, he
OL,20,Fmentioned "its use in aeroplanes".
OL,3,CHydrogen-powered planes: the future of
OL,4,Ctravel, or just a fantasy?
